turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: There's no <INAUDIBLE_SPEECH/>. <UNIN/>, hello?

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: <UNIN/>. Hi there.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: Hello there. Um, thanks for, thanks for, being here. Um, before I go any further, can I uh, confirm your name and your age please?

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: Yes, it's um Adriana Katherine <UNIN/>. And I'm twenty six year old.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: <INAUDIBLE_SPEECH/>

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: OK, Adriana, and how can I help you this afternoon?

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: Well, I have this like really crazy headache that's been going on for a few days. And it really annoys me.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: Ohh dear, OK. <UNIN/>, when, when did it exactly start, this headache?

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: Eh, around three days ago, maybe.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: Three <UNSURE>days</UNSURE> ago, OK. And whereabout in your head, is this pain?

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: Um, it's basically like, it kind of feels all over my head, but like mainly, um, around my right eye. Um

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: <INAUDIBLE_SPEECH/>, OK. Um, and is the, headache there all the time, or does it come and go?

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: Um it's, it kind of comes and goes. Um but, I mean it is there all the time, but <UNIN/> like sometimes it's stronger.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: OK, so it comes and, fine, OK. And if I was to ask you on a scale of one to ten, um, ten being the worst type of pain you ever had. How would you rate this headache?

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: Ohh it's probably a eight.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: <UNSURE>Eight</UNSURE>. And if I was to ask you describe the headache to me, um, in terms of the nature of the pain. Is it sharp? Is it dull? Is it crampy? Is it throbbing?

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: Um, it's kind of, it's dull but sometimes it gets a bit sharper. So basically it like, it developed gradually, I guess. It's like the first day it just started when I was at work.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: Mm-hmm.

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: And by the end of the day it was like pretty, pretty, like it was a lot, basically. And then I was thinking OK, maybe I'll just go to sleep. And when I woke up the next morning like, it was even, even worse basically. So

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: Mm-hmm.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: So, you think the headache is getting worse over the last three days?

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: Yeah.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: OK. Have you tried anything which has made the headache better?

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: Um so I tried uh Ibuprofen. Um so I took, like a few. Um for the last two days, basically.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: Did that <UNSURE>help</UNSURE>?

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: But it doesn't really help, no. In in the past it did help me, which is why I decided to try it. But

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: OK, all right. And except for the headaches, any other symptoms at all?

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: Um

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: So, <UNSURE>example</UNSURE> any, problems your eyesight or your vision?

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: Not really, but just when it started, I I got this like weird shooting lights. And like now like light is quite annoying, my eyes.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: So when you say annoying, does it hurt to look, uh, look at bright lights?

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: Yeah, yeah. It hurts. So

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: <UNIN/>, OK. And um, have you had any loss of vision or blurry vision?

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: Not loss of vision, I wouldn't say. It's just like some lights from, shooting lights <INAUDIBLE_SPEECH/>.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: <UNSURE>Mmm</UNSURE>, <UNIN/>, <UNSURE>OK</UNSURE>. Any nausea or any vomiting?

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: Um, well I'm like basically, I I'm sick with the headache. But I, no vomiting.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: When you say sick, you mean you feel sick? OK. Yeah, no vomiting, OK. Any neck pain or neck stiffness?

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: Yeah.

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: No.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: OK. And any difficulty with speaking or, um, speech?

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: No.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: Any difficulty <UNIN/>, with weakness in your arms and legs?

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: No, it's hard to focus though. So, I I had to take a couple of days off work, actually.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: Ohh really? OK. OK, <UNSURE>yeah probably</UNSURE>, well I'll, I'll ask you a bit more about your work later on. Um, any recent head injuries at all?

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: Uh, no.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: OK. And have you had anything like this before in the past?

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: Yeah I mean, headaches, you mean.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: Or, uh, or similar, similar to, similar to this kind of headache, <INAUDIBLE_SPEECH/>?

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: Yeah. I mean I had. But, usually after I I take uh Ibuprofen it kind of goes away. So, but this time it's just not. <INAUDIBLE_SPEECH/>.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: <INAUDIBLE_SPEECH/> not, OK. All right. Um, any temperatures, or fevers?

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: No.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: Any rashes at all, on your skin?

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: Mm, no not that I've noticed.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: OK. And just moving forwards. Are you otherwise fit and well, Adriana?

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: Am I what, sorry?

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: You fit and well? <UNIN/>, do you have any other medical <UNSURE>history</UNSURE>?

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: Yeah, I think so. It's just the headache.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: Any history of migraines at all?

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: Not myself, I've never had a migraine. But my sister and my mom have them quite frequently.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: OK. Um, fine. I'll ask you a bit more about that in just a second. Before I go any further, can I ask, do you take any regular medication?

turns.text: Uh, no no.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: Are you on the pill?

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: OK. Do you have any allergies to any medications?

turns.text: Mm not that I know of.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: OK. So you mentioned your mother and sister both have migraines.

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: Yeah.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: Are they, is that normally well-controlled or are they um, having difficulty, controlling their symptoms?

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: Um so my sister's, like better. Like it's kind of, it's very rare. But my mom's is like quite bad, um usually when there's like a season changing and stuff like that. It's, yeah.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: <UNSURE>Mm-hmm, OK</UNSURE>.

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: Takes her out for a few days, basically.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: Ohh right, OK, fine. Um, socially, tell me a bit more about your life, outside of, um, outside of, work. So <UNIN/>, who lives at home with you?

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: Uh I live with housemates. So, three of them. So we're four <UNIN/>.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: <UNSURE>OK</UNSURE>. Excellent. And are you working at the moment? You mentioned this <UNIN/>, impacting on your work.

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: Yeah so I work, well I work in IT. So I work with computers a lot. So it kind of is difficult to focus. Um I had to like reduce the uh, brightness of my screen.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: <UNSURE>Mmm</UNSURE>. OK. Do you wear glasses?

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: Yes, I do.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: Have you had any, uh, have you had any recent eye check, done? Eye test?

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: No, uh I've been wearing them since I was five <UNIN/>, five year old. <UNSURE> So, it's quite a long time.</UNSURE>

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: OK, all right. Something for you to bear in mind if you feel that you are, your eyes are straining. Um I would always recommend having a repeat eye test done. Um, have you been feeling more stressed or anxious at work recently?

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: <INAUDIBLE_SPEECH/>

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: Well, it's been a bit stressful, kicking off a new project. But um, yeah nothing out of the ordinary, really.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: OK, all right. Great. Um, regarding smoking or alcohol. Do you drink or smoke at all?

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: I socially smoke. And I drink <UNIN/> only socially.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: <UNSURE>But</UNSURE> only socially?

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: OK.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: Right. Now um, Adriana, do you have any ideas as to what could be causing your symptoms? Have you, have you read anything online, or spoken to people?

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: Um

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: Not really. Um <INAUDIBLE_SPEECH/> at first I thought it's stress, or maybe I didn't drink enough water. Because sometimes when I don't drink enough water, I I like get headaches. Um

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: Mm-hmm.

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: But, I don't think that's it. And I'm like worried, it's, I don't want it to be a migraine. Because I know what it's like, from my mom and my sister.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: <INAUDIBLE_SPEECH/>

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: Mmm.

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: And it's really annoying. So I I really don't want to have that. And I know it's genetic. So I've researched that. Um but I don't know if that is the case. So, yeah.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: OK. Is <UNSURE>it</UNSURE> anything in particular you were hoping I could do for you today?

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: Yeah maybe just kinda, if you have any recommendations of <UNIN/> that I can take something stronger. Because apparently, Ibuprofen doesn't help me. Uh

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: <UNSURE>OK</UNSURE>.

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: Usually it gets resolved if I have headache in like, after like one or two days. But currently it, it didn't help me.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: How many tablets did you take of Ibuprofen?

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: Uh, three a day.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: Three a day, OK. All right. Um, so uh, Adriana, so um, really what I think is going on here. I <UNIN/>, uh, unfortunately I do think this could be, a headache very similar to a migraine.

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: <INAUDIBLE_SPEECH/>

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: Um, the reason I say that is because the history is very suggestive of it, given your mum and your sister also migraines. I think it's something for us to think about.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: Um, now I'm not saying it's gonna, keep happening, but, it may just be a one-off. But it's certainly worth treating it today stronger <UNSURE>analgesia or</UNSURE> painkillers.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: Um, now moving forward, we have some options which we can discuss. Uh, you tried the Ibuprofen. Now, my only worry is, I'm not sure whether you're taking, the correct dose. You can take up to two tablets, three times a day.

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: Ohh right.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: <UNSURE>So</UNSURE>, so <UNIN/>, there's definitely room for, improvement there. Or, I can prescribe you something stronger, like Naproxen, which is another anti-inflammatory, which can be helpful.

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: Mm-hmm.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: <UNSURE>Um</UNSURE>, we can also add in other, painkillers like, Paracetamol, or Codeine. Which might be helpful as well.

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: Mm, yeah. I think <UNIN/> is what my mom takes for when she has um, um migraines.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: OK. And I think it's <UNIN/>, certainly worth looking into that, so I can give you a <UNIN/>, prescription for that today. Um, with regards to um, the next few days. It may be worth keeping a headache diary so we can try and work out what's, you know, if there's any triggers which could be causing your headaches to become worse.

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: Mm-hmm.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: <UNSURE>And</UNSURE>, and, you know I'd like you to come back and see me, in about uh, a week's time, week to two weeks' time.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: If you are having <UNIN/>, more frequent episodes of these type of headaches. We can think about giving you medications as, prophylactic. Which basically means, medications to stop you from having these headaches on a regular basis. But we can have that discussion next time.

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: Mm, OK.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: OK. In the meantime if your headaches aren't getting any better, or they're getting worse. Um, you know, I want you to give me a call, or come back and see me sooner. OK?

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: OK. Yeah.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: So, <UNSURE>if</UNSURE> you're having any problems with your vision, or weakness in your arms and legs, or you're just not feeling very well. Just give me a call, and come back and see me.

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: OK.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: All right?

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: Great.
